19_0	0.0	NEW YORK (AP) --Vioxx, the highly anticipated new pain pill from Merck &AMP; Co.
19_1	0.0	Inc. that promises to be easier on the stomach than aspirin, works well in relieving menstrual and post-surgical pain, according to two company studies unveiled today at a medical meeting.
19_2	0.0	Vioxx is expected to reach pharmacies later this spring after obtaining approval from the federal Food and Drug Administration.
19_3	0.043478260869565216	Vioxx was as effective as prescription-strength Aleve, an aspirin-type drug, in treating moderate to severe menstrual pain, according to a Merck study of 127 women being presented at the American Society of Clinical Pharmacology and Therapeutics in San Antonio, Texas.
19_4	0.375	The study found pain relief was sustained for at least 12 hours.
19_5	0.23529411764705882	In a second study of 151 patients who had oral surgery to remove their wisdom teeth, Vioxx proved as effective at postoperative pain relief as ibuprofen.
19_6	0.16666666666666666	The dental study also showed one 50 milligram Vioxx pill could provide relief for a full 24 hours.
19_7	0.0	Ibuprofen must be taken at least three times a day.
19_8	0.15789473684210525	Vioxx will likely become the second in a new class of pain medications which work as well as aspirin and other anti-inflammatory medicines but don't cause stomach irritation that can lead to ulcers and other dangerous ailments.
19_9	0.0	Merck, the world's largest drug company, will be playing catch-up to Monsanto Co.'s Celebrex drug, which won U.S. approval on Dec.
19_10	0.0	31. Celebrex, approved for osteoarthritis and rheumatoid arthritis, has already sold more than 1.1 million prescriptions, making it the biggest new drug of 1999.
19_11	0.0	It has also has become the second-fastest-selling new drug in history after Pfizer Inc.'s impotence pill Viagra.
19_12	0.3333333333333333	Like Celebrex, Merck is looking to get approval for Vioxx to treat osteoarthritis, which affects more than 16 million Americans.
19_13	0.2	But instead of also seeking indication for rheumatoid arthritis, which affects about 2 million Americans, it wants the FDA to approve Vioxx for acute pain treatment --a market of more than 40 million Americans.
19_14	0.0	It's for this reason that Merck is giving the FDA data showing how the drug works against different types of pain.
19_15	0.19047619047619047	Though the risk of stomach ailments is higher when taking aspirin and other anti-inflammatory drugs for prolonged use, a dilemma faced most arthritis sufferers, the gastrointestinal risks exist even with short duration use, experts say.
